    ("h2", "1.5 The Problem of Duplicate Observations and Variable Endpoints"),
    ("p", "Deduplication is a critical step in compiling training datasets for QSAR modeling. Public databases contain duplicate observations for identical compounds, which can bias model predictions if left unresolved. The challenge is compounded when these duplicate records report conflicting toxicity values, representing experimental group variance [fourches2016importance]. In conventional workflows, researchers often delete conflicting records or apply a simple average, hiding the underlying variance. SUTRIX introduces an interactive data curation workspace that offers five group variance strategies (including KEEP_ALL, KEEP_MEDIAN, and REMOVE_CONFLICTS), allowing researchers to compare strategies and maintain full transparent control over data reduction."),
